{
  "text": "Contemporary demographic processes also shape the patterns of genetic diversity and structure in striped skunks. The signal of a population bottleneck found in the microsatellite data from the Northwest population at 1st appears to contradict the results of the mitochondrial data, which indicated steady population expansion of striped skunks throughout North America. However, striped skunks are reservoirs for many diseases including rabies [CITATION_1] ), canine distemper [CITATION_2] , and tularemia [CITATION_3] . California and the Great Plains are the foci of 3 strains of rabies for which striped skunks are the major disease reservoir [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Rabies is virtually always fatal, and routinely decimates populations of striped skunk where the disease is endemic, leading to periodic fluctuations in population size [CITATION_6] , the signature of which was likely captured by the bottleneck test. The East population, on the other hand, does not have an endemic strain of skunk rabies (although striped skunks succumb to the raccoon strain in the east- [CITATION_7] and in this population we found no evidence of a population bottleneck.",
